Problem 1

The convolution can be used to find the probability of the sum or average of probability distributions. For a telescope searching for a gamma-ray source, the noise from the cosmic ray background will be Poisson distributed. If we know the average of the background and the average of our source for a one day period, can we determine the likelihood that the background will produce something as signal-like or more than our source over a period of days?
A) The probability distribution of the background changes as we integrate (sum) for more days:
clc; clear; close all;
X = 2; % average cosmic-ray background in 1 day
Y = 7; % average number of gamma-rays emitted by hypothetical source
onedaypoisson = makedist("Poisson","lambda",X);
xaxis = 0:1:20;
pdfoneday = pdf(onedaypoisson,xaxis); % quantized pdf
pdfoneday = pdfoneday/sum(pdfoneday); % normalized pdf
plot(xaxis,pdfoneday,"LineWidth",3); % if plotting stairs then shift half interval
hold on;
% plotting convolutions
pdftwoday = conv(pdfoneday,pdfoneday);
plot(0:length(pdftwoday)-1,pdftwoday,"LineWidth",3);
pdfthreeday = conv(pdftwoday,pdfoneday);
plot(0:length(pdfthreeday)-1,pdfthreeday,"LineWidth",3);
pdffourday = conv(pdfthreeday,pdfoneday);
plot(0:length(pdffourday)-1,pdffourday,"LineWidth",3);
pdffiveday = conv(pdffourday,pdfoneday);
plot(0:length(pdffiveday)-1,pdffiveday,"LineWidth",3);
xlim ([0,20]);
xlabel("Sum of Counts")
ylabel("Probability");
title("Convolutions (Sum) of Poisson Cosmic Background");
legend("Original Distribution","1st Convolution","2nd Convolution","3rd Convolution","4th Convolution");
hold off;
B) After 5 days, the summed probability distribution will still be a Poisson distribution:
pdfsixday = conv(pdffiveday,pdfoneday);
plot(0:length(pdfsixday)-1,pdfsixday,"LineWidth",4);
xlim([0,25]);
hold on;
mean = dot(pdfsixday,0:length(pdfsixday)-1);
sixdaytest = makedist("Poisson","lambda",mean);
plot(0:length(pdfsixday)-1,pdf(sixdaytest,0:length(pdfsixday)-1),"LineStyle","--","LineWidth",4);
xlabel("Counts");
ylabel("Probability");
title("Six Day Poisson Distribution of Cosmic Background");
legend("Six Day Poisson","Test Poisson");
hold off;
The Poisson distribution tells us the probability of having some number of random independent events occur for a fixed interval. It is centered about the average number of events and the sum of the probabilities for all outcomes is 1. We can use convolutions to quickly produce the distributions of the summed outcomes. The sums of independent variables are themselves independent, the summed probabilities of these new distribution are still 1, and the new means are the sum of means of the Poissons that were convoluted together (the mean is larger because the sum of whole numbers is typically larger than what you start with).
Conceptually, we expect that if we were to calculate the distribution for the background for two days without the convolution that we would get twice the counts and still be Poisson distributed because we are still dealing with random independent events over a fixed time interval. It's no surprise then that the summed probability distributions would remain Poisson.
C) The evolution of the probability distribution as we average days:
% Scaling just the x-axis gives the just the probability for the
% average. I've chosen to normalize the area for these plots by also scaling the y-axis
% (now giving DISCRETE probability density) to demonstrate how the shape of the
% distribution evolves towards a CONTINUOUS Gaussian distribution.
plot(xaxis,pdfoneday,"LineWidth",4);
hold on;
plot((0:length(pdftwoday)-1)/2.0,pdftwoday*2,"LineWidth",2);
plot((0:length(pdfthreeday)-1)/3.0,pdfthreeday*3,"LineWidth",2);
plot((0:length(pdffourday)-1)/4.0,pdffourday*4,"LineWidth",2);
plot((0:length(pdffiveday)-1)/5.0,pdffiveday*5,"LineWidth",2);
plot((0:length(pdfsixday)-1)/6.0,pdfsixday*6,"LineWidth",2);
pdfold = pdfsixday;
for x = 7:30 % loop to generate plots for more convolutions
pdfnew = conv(pdfoneday,pdfold);
plot((0:length(pdfnew)-1)/x,pdfnew*x,"LineWidth",2);
pdfold = pdfnew;
end
xlim([0,6]);
xlabel("Average of Counts");
ylabel("Discrete Probability Density");
title("Convolutions (Average) of Poisson Cosmic Background");
legend("Original Background","Averaged Backgrounds");
hold off;
% gaussian test
x30 = (0:length(pdfnew)-1)/x;
mean30 = dot(x30,pdfnew) % sum of products of x and prob(x)
mean30 = 2.0000
vari30 = dot((x30 - mean30).^2,pdfnew) % calculating variance
vari30 = 0.0667
gaussdist30 = makedist("Normal","mu",mean30,"sigma",sqrt(vari30));
gausspdf30 = pdf(gaussdist30,x30);
sum(gausspdf30) % gauss is a probability density
ans = 30.0000
sum(pdfnew) % poisson is a discrete probability
ans = 1.0000
plot((0:length(pdfnew)-1)/x,pdfnew*x,"LineWidth",3);
hold on;
plot(x30,gausspdf30,"LineStyle","--","LineWidth",3);
xlim([1,3]);
xlabel("Average Count");
ylabel("Probability Density");
title("30 Day Average Poisson Distribution of Cosmic Background");
legend("30 Day Poisson","Test Gaussian");
As we increase the number of days, the distribution pulls in and becomes more sharply peaked at the mean. In B) the sum distribution was still a Poisson distribution as it spread out and moved its mean to the right, but because the Poisson distribution approximates a Gaussian for very large means (a consequence of the central limit theorem) then as our mean increases with each convolution the distribution also becomes more Gaussian. The central limit theorem says that the distribution for the sums or means of many samples of random independent observations will approximate a Gaussian distribution. We've now seen here that both the sum and average distributions become more Gaussian as we perform more convolutions.
D) Calculating the 'sigma' of our observation after a period of days:
% Since we will use total gamma-rays over a period of days, we should use the sum distribution.
N = 5; % number of days
Y % average number of gamma-rays per day from source
Y = 7
rays = Y*N % total number of gamma-rays seen from source
rays = 35
% finding mean of the PMF
mean5 = dot(pdffiveday,(0:length(pdffiveday)-1)) % same mean as the sum of 5 convolution
mean5 = 10.0000
% creating poisson distribution with same mean as day 5
pdf5test = makedist("Poisson","lambda",mean5);
prob = cdf(pdf5test,rays,'upper')
prob = 1.6667e-10
sigma = abs(norminv(prob))
sigma = 6.2824
The 'sigma' of our observation is over 6.

Problem 2

We will now observe changes in a background which follows a skewed continuous Rayleigh distribution.
A) Showing how the distribution changes when averaged over more observing intervals:
clc; clear; close all;
dist = makedist("Rayleigh","b",10);
x = 0:50;
pdfray = pdf(dist,x);
sum(pdfray) % THIS is a big problem
ans = 0.9992
pdfray = pdfray/sum(pdfray); % normalize to fix
sum(pdfray)
ans = 1.0000
plot(x,pdfray,"LineWidth",2);
hold on;
pdfold = pdfray;
% plotting many averages with a loop
for k = 2:40 % needs to be VERY high (1000+) to bring edges in on log plot
pdfnew = conv(pdfray,pdfold,'full');
plot((0:(length(pdfnew)-1))/k,pdfnew*k);
pdfold = pdfnew;
end
xlabel("Value");
ylabel("Probability Density");
title("Convolutions (Average) of Rayleigh Background");
legend("Original PDF","Convoluted PDFs");
xlim([0,35]);
hold off;
% NOTE ON NORMALIZATION: The conv() MATLAB command convolutes discrete vector values and the
% resulting probabilities should add to 1 if the original pdf() values were properly normalized.
% HOWEVER, the plot of a CONTINUOUS PDF has the probability DENSITY on the vertical axis, NOT the
% probability. Here we are plotting continuous distributions but are still convoluting with discrete
% values. The pdf() command now produces probability DENSITY values which may not sum to 1.0000 depending
% on the range and step size of the x-values we feed it. When normalizing and convoluting, we must not
% forget that these are density values which MUST be scaled when plotting to preserve
% the area under the continuous distribution as it changes, hence why we multiply the y-values to
% counter the area loss caused by division of x-values when averaging.
%
% We expect the area under a continuous PDF to remain 1.0000 by definition. We can easily check if
% this method of plotting works:
trapz(x,pdfray)
ans = 1.0000
trapz((0:(length(pdfnew)-1))/k,pdfnew*k)
ans = 1.0000
B) We see the sides pull in as we settle about a mean value. The Rayleigh distribution also appears to be approaching a Gaussian. How many intervals are required until we are confidant that it is?
% testing against a gaussian
x1 = (0:(numel(pdfnew)-1))/k;
sum(pdfnew) % this should still be 1.0000 if the initial distribution was properly normalized
ans = 1.0000
mean = dot(x1,(pdfnew)) % sum of products of x and prob(x)
mean = 12.5435
vari = dot((x1 - mean).^2,pdfnew) % calculating variance
vari = 1.0705
% making a Gaussian distribution with these values
gaussdist = makedist("Normal","mu",mean,"sigma",sqrt(vari));
gausspdf = pdf(gaussdist,x1);
plot(x1,pdfnew*k,"LineWidth",3); % original plot
hold on;
plot(x1,gausspdf,"LineStyle","--","LineWidth",3); % Gaussian plot
xlim([0,30]);
xlabel("Value");
ylabel("Probability Density");
title("Rayleigh Background After Many Convolutions (Average)");
legend("Final Convolution","Test Gaussian");
hold off;
plot(x1,pdfnew*k,"LineWidth",3);
hold on;
plot(x1,gausspdf,"LineStyle","--","LineWidth",3);
xlim([0,30]);
set(gca,'YScale','log');
xlabel("Value");
ylabel("Probability Density");
title("Log Plot of Convoluted (Average) Rayleigh Background");
legend("Final Convolution","Test Gaussian");
Graphing a Gaussian with the same mean and standard deviation shows that they are close, and getting closer as we perform more convolutions. To approach a Gaussian it needs about 50 to overlap cleanly with the standard plot above. The log plot slowly improves with continued convolutions but will require many, many more to be convincing.

Problem 3

We are looking for the optical emission that matches a gravity-wave signal from Neutron star mergers using an optical telescope with a zero-mean background Gaussian distribution X with constant width, searching for a signal Y (floating-point value). LIGO, the Laser Interfermeter Gravitational-Wave Observatory, sends out an alert that an event has occurred.
A) With some outside assistance from SWIFT, an X-ray/ultra-violet satellite, I am told which pixel to look in. Seeing a signal of strength Y, what is the significance of my detection? Can I claim a discovery?
clc; clear; close all;
X = makedist("Normal","mu",0,"sigma",2); % background Gaussian distribution
Y = 13.1; % signal strength, floating point
prob = cdf(X,Y,'upper');
sigma = abs(norminv(prob))
sigma = 6.5500
Yes, I can claim a discovery because this is more than 5-sigma, the traditional threshold.
B) If I don't know which pixel to look in, so I instead search through 10,000 in total, what now is the probability distribution of the background?
The probability distribution of my background will be the original single pixel background scaled by a trial factor of 10,000 because we have to look in 10,000 places each with the same (cumulative) chance of the background producing the signal (or something more signal-like).
C) The probability that the signal-free background will produce something that looks as much or more signal-like is now the area under the distribution scaled by the trial factor. This is also the total sum of the (identical) probabilities for each pixel, or in this case just the product of the single pixel probability with the trial factor of 10,000.
tenkprob = 10000*prob
tenkprob = 2.8769e-07
tenksigma = abs(norminv(tenkprob))
tenksigma = 4.9993
Unfortunately, the significance is now just a hair under 5 sigma. Because the background was given more opportunities to produce something as or more signal-like than what I was looking for, the area under the normal distribution grew and lowered the significance of this detection.

Problem 4

It is important to always consider the trial factor that we encountered above. Can we get an estimate for how much this will impact our searches?
% same distribution as in Problem 3
clc; clear; close all;
X = makedist("Normal","mu",0,"sigma",2);
trials = 10000;
A) Calculating the 5-sigma signal detection threshold for a single pixel:
fivesigma = normcdf(5,'upper')
fivesigma = 2.8665e-07
det1 = icdf(X,1-fivesigma)
det1 = 10.0000
We need a signal of 10.
B) Calculating the 5-sigma signal detection threshold for 10,000 pixels:
det2 = icdf(X,1-fivesigma/trials)
det2 = 13.1011
We now need a signal of 13.1011.
C) Plotting graphs to demonstrate how much brighter the signals have to be:
xvals = 0:0.1:50;
pixelpdf = pdf(X,xvals);
pixelspdf = pixelpdf*trials;
subplot(1,2,1);
plot(xvals,pixelpdf,"LineWidth",2); % plot of 1 pixel
xlabel("Signal Value");
ylabel("Probability Density");
title("1 Pixel");
hold on;
stem(det1,pixelpdf(round(det1*10+1)),"LineWidth",2);
legend("Background Gaussian","5-Sigma Threshold");
hold off;
xlim([det1-1,det1+1]);
ylim([0,3E-6]);
subplot(1,2,2);
plot(xvals,pixelspdf,"LineWidth",2); % plot of 10000 pixels
xlabel("Signal Value");
title("10,000 Pixels");
hold on;
stem(det2,pixelspdf(round(det2*10+1)),"LineWidth",2);
legend("Background Gaussian","5-Sigma Threshold");
hold off;
xlim([det2-1,det2+1]);
ylim([0,3E-6]);
The signal only needs to be a little over 3 units brighter. The sensitivity penalty for the trials factor is low because the probability (area) falls off so rapidly far away from the mean that we don't need to move much to make up for it.
D) What happens to the threshold when I change the trials factor significantly (orders of magnitude)?
% orders of magnitude 10^x
values = [];
for x = -4:5 % for trial factors 1, 10, 100, 1000, 10000, 100000, etc.
values = [values,icdf(X,1-fivesigma/(trials*10^x))];
end
values
values = 110
10.0000 10.8539 11.6487 12.3952 13.1011 13.7723 14.4134 15.0283 15.6176 16.1531
diff(values)
ans = 19
0.8539 0.7949 0.7465 0.7059 0.6712 0.6411 0.6149 0.5893 0.5355
The effect on my 5-sigma sensitivity threshold is less than 1 (and decreasing) for each successive order of magnitude.
Extra credit:
For a differently shaped distribution, the sensitivity penalty will be affected by how quickly that distribution falls off at larger signals. Longer tails, such as in an exponential distribution, will feature a higher sensitivity penalty than ones with short tails like the normal distribution.
